## 3. Performance & Scalability

### 🟠 FLAW PERF-01: Store Landing Page Has Sequential N+1 Pattern

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟠 **HIGH** |
| **Location** | [app/[storeType]/page.tsx:34-57](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/app/%5BstoreType%5D/page.tsx#L34-L57) |
| **The Flaw** | The store home page performs 8+ database queries: products, hero images, home video, lookbook items, section visibility, home categories, all categories, then a follow-up query for product colors. While `Promise.all` is used (good!), the query for `allCats` (line 47: `db.select().from(productCategories)`) fetches **all** categories regardless of store type and doesn't appear to be used in the rendered JSX. |
| **The "Why"** | Unnecessary data fetching increases response time and database load. As the product catalog grows, these queries will slow down page loads. The `allCats` query appears to be dead code. |
| **Recommendation** | 1) Remove the unused `allCats` query. 2) Consider using Drizzle's relational queries to fetch products with their first color image in a single query. 3) Implement database connection pooling (check that Transaction mode on Supabase is being used — the port `:6543` in the connection string confirms this, which is good). |

---

### 🟠 FLAW PERF-02: `unoptimized` Flag on Next/Image

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟠 **HIGH** |
| **Location** | [app/page.tsx:29, 55](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/app/page.tsx#L29), [app/[storeType]/page.tsx:84, 119, 158, 199](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/app/%5BstoreType%5D/page.tsx) |
| **The Flaw** | Many `<Image>` components use `unoptimized` or `unoptimized={imageUrl.startsWith("https://")}`. This bypasses Next.js Image Optimization, which handles format conversion (WebP/AVIF), resizing, and lazy loading. |
| **The "Why"** | Without optimization, users download full-resolution images (potentially several MB each), dramatically increasing page load time, especially on mobile. For an e-commerce site with image-heavy pages, this directly impacts conversion rates (). Google reports 53% of users abandon sites that take >3s to load. |
| **Recommendation** | 1) Remove `unoptimized` prop from all images. 2) Add proper `sizes` attributes, e.g., `sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 50vw"`. 3) The `remotePatterns` in `next.config.ts` already covers Supabase and Pexels domains, so optimization will work automatically. 4) For conditionally-unoptimized images (external URLs), ensure all external domains are registered in `remotePatterns`. |

---

### 🟡 FLAW PERF-03: In-Memory Rate Limiter Won't Work in Production

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟡 **MEDIUM** |
| **Location** | [lib/rate-limit.ts](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/lib/rate-limit.ts) |
| **The Flaw** | The rate limiter uses an in-memory `Map`. Deployed to Vercel or any serverless/multi-instance platform, each instance maintains its own Map, so rate limits are per-instance, not global. |
| **The "Why"** | An attacker hitting multiple instances can bypass rate limits entirely. The code even has a comment acknowledging this: "For production multi-instance deployments, replace with a Redis-based limiter." |
| **Recommendation** | For production: 1) Use `@upstash/ratelimit` with Upstash Redis (serverless-compatible, free tier available). 2) Or use Vercel Edge Middleware with `@vercel/kv`. The interface is similar so migration is straightforward. |

---

### 🟡 FLAW PERF-04: Missing Database Indexes

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟡 **MEDIUM** |
| **Location** | [db/schema.ts](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/db/schema.ts) |
| **The Flaw** | No explicit indexes are defined on frequently queried columns: `products.storeType`, `products.categorySlug`, `products.isVisible`, `orders.userId`, `wishlists.userId + productId` (composite), `productColors.productId`, `productVariants.productId + size` (composite). |
| **The "Why"** | Without indexes, the database performs full table scans for filtered queries. As the product catalog grows past hundreds of items, shop page loads and admin queries will degrade significantly. The composite `wishlists(userId, productId)` index is especially critical as it's used in a tight "check if exists, then insert/delete" pattern. |
| **Recommendation** | Add indexes to the schema: ```typescript
import { index, uniqueIndex } from "drizzle-orm/pg-core";
// On wishlists table:
// .index("wishlists_user_product_idx", [wishlists.userId, wishlists.productId])
// On products:
// .index("products_store_visible_idx", [products.storeType, products.isVisible])
``` Generate and run a migration after adding. |

---

### 🟢 FLAW PERF-05: Navbar is Client Component at Root Layout

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟢 **LOW** |
| **Location** | [app/layout.tsx:38](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/app/layout.tsx#L38), [components/Navbar.tsx](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/components/Navbar.tsx) (13KB) |
| **The Flaw** | The `Navbar` component (13KB) is rendered in the root layout for **every** page, including admin pages that have their own sidebar. It's a `"use client"` component, which means the 13KB JavaScript bundle is always shipped. |
| **The "Why"** | Admin pages have their own navigation, but still load the storefront Navbar. This is unnecessary JavaScript and renders a component that may either be hidden or conflicting with the admin layout. |
| **Recommendation** | Conditionally render the Navbar based on the route, or create separate layout groups: [(storefront)](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/lib/utils.ts#4-7) and [(admin)](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/lib/utils.ts#4-7), each with its own layout. Next.js route groups ([(group)](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/lib/utils.ts#4-7)) are designed for exactly this. |

