## 5. Privacy & Compliance

### 🟡 FLAW PRIV-01: `adminStore` Cookie Lacks Privacy-Safe Configuration

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟡 **MEDIUM** |
| **Location** | [actions/admin-store.ts:10](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/actions/admin-store.ts#L10) |
| **The Flaw** | The `adminStore` cookie is set without `SameSite`, `Secure`, or `HttpOnly` attributes. It also has no expiration, making it a session cookie by default. (This overlaps with SEC-02 but is called out specifically for privacy.) |
| **The "Why"** | European cookie regulations (ePrivacy Directive) require cookies to be set with appropriate security attributes. An overly-permissive cookie can be used for cross-site tracking attacks. |
| **Recommendation** | See SEC-02 recommendation. Additionally, consider documenting this cookie in a privacy policy. |

---

### 🟡 FLAW PRIV-02: No Right-to-Deletion Architecture for User Data

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟡 **MEDIUM** |
| **Location** | [db/schema.ts](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/db/schema.ts) — `orders`, `wishlists` |
| **The Flaw** | There's no mechanism to delete or anonymize a user's data. The `orders` table stores `userId`, `guestEmail`, `customerName`, `phoneNumber`, and `addressLine1` indefinitely. The `wishlists` table stores `userId`. There's no "delete my account" action or data export function. |
| **The "Why"** | GDPR (Art. 17 "Right to Erasure") and similar regulations (CCPA) require the ability to delete all personal data upon request. Without this capability, the platform cannot be compliant. |
| **Recommendation** | 1) Create a `deleteUserData(userId)` server action that: anonymizes orders (replace PII with "DELETED"), deletes wishlists, and triggers Clerk user deletion. 2) Add an "Account Settings" page with a "Delete my account" option. 3) Consider implementing soft-delete with time-based hard purging for orders (retain anonymized financial records for tax compliance). |

---

### 🟢 FLAW PRIV-03: Cart Data in localStorage Without User Consent

| Attribute | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Risk Level** | 🟢 **LOW** |
| **Location** | [context/CartContext.tsx:59-78](file:///c:/Users/PC%20FACTORY/Desktop/MosaikWeb/context/CartContext.tsx#L59-L78) |
| **The Flaw** | Cart data (product IDs, sizes, quantities, prices) is stored in `localStorage` without user consent. While localStorage is functionally necessary, it persists indefinitely. |
| **The "Why"** | Under ePrivacy regulations, some interpretations require consent for any client-side storage beyond what's "strictly necessary." Cart persistence across sessions could be argued as not strictly necessary (it's a user convenience). |
| **Recommendation** | 1) Consider using `sessionStorage` instead (cleared when tab closes). 2) Or add a cart data clearing mechanism (e.g., clear after 30 days). 3) Document localStorage usage in the privacy policy. |

